## USER RESEARCH

### Top 5 Pain Points

1. **"The nude I chose looks grey / dirty / wrong on me"** — most common complaint across TikTok and forum content; readers buy or book a nude shade that looks beautiful in the bottle but turns muddy, chalky, or ghostly on their actual hand. They don't understand why and don't know how to fix it. Root cause: undertone mismatch.

2. **"Trending colours don't work on my skin tone"** — audience watches viral nail content (butter yellow moment, milky white, etc.) and tries to replicate it, only to find the colour looks washed out or clashes with their complexion. Specifically called out by celebrity manicurists re: butter yellow in 2026 (documented in Who What Wear / CM Nails Supply).

3. **"I can never find the right nude / skin-tone-matching shade for dark/brown skin"** — TikTok hashtag volume around #browngirl nails, #blackgirltiktok almondnails, dark skin nail searches is very high; content creators repeatedly address this. Community frustration: most "nude" shade ranges cater to lighter skin tones.

4. **"I don't know my undertone / how to figure it out"** — readers know undertone matters but find the advice confusing or contradictory; they want a fast, reliable method. Vein test, jewellery test, paper test are repeatedly referenced in community posts as the most practical.

5. **"Will this colour make my hands look older / shorter / wider?"** — shape-specific anxiety that intersects with colour choice; audience on TikTok comments and nail forums frequently asks whether a colour (especially very pale or very dark) will make fingers look shorter, skin look older, or make hands look bigger. Almond shape is chosen specifically to elongate, so anything that disrupts that is a concern.

**User Sentiment:** Aspirational but anxious — readers want to look polished and current, but are regularly let down by colour choices that seemed right online and went wrong in real life.

